The film is an adaption of Alan Glynn‚Äôs novel. Released on March 18, 2011, the film became an instant box-office success.¬†

A mysterious nootropic enables Eddie (B.Cooper) to access one hundred percent of his brain abilities. He gets on his feet again: the pill brings him a job on financial markets but also puts him in danger. After numerous twists and turns, there‚Äôs a nail-biting finale. It just seems too good to be true and that is primarily what grips you through this well-paced screenplay.

It‚Äôs a big budget movie with a powerful performance from the actors. The movie has some hair-raising chases and mind-blowing scenes. Having a fast-moving story, the film really keeps your eyes on the screen and makes your heart to beat faster. The only weakness I would think is worth mentioning, is that the film may be really violent, which would not be necessary.¬†

I found the film really far-fetching since our society is built upon a life, where people are forced to be successful but don‚Äôt have a work-life balance. The movie amused me and it‚Äôs pure 105 min of joy when you are into action and handsome actors.

When I was 19-years-old, I used to see Chuck Wepner every morning standing at the entrance gates as all of the factory workers walked through the gates into the noisy polluted air of the Western Electric factory, a city unto itself on the west bank of the Passaic River in Kearny, New Jersey. At the time (1972) Wepner was a security guard in a full-fledged police uniform.  The factory was so enormous it had its own police and fire departments, and an indoor mall that the workers could buy clothes, shoes, and other clothing accessories at.  At night, the workers would drive in a line of 30-40 dump trucks filled with poison refuse, that they secretly dumped into the Passaic River. Afterward, at lunchtime, I would stand on the east bank of the Passaic River, where for three days you could see an almost endless assembly line of dead fish floating north down the river. I used to wonder how many hundreds of millions of fish they had killed during their polluted existence of this environmental disaster of a factory that lasted several decades. It was a sad and disgusting sight to see. During WWII, this factory employed about 75,000 people which operated around the clock twenty-four hours a day.  During this time, I used to go and watch Chuck Wepner box frequently. He was sort of my hero because I felt I knew him on a somewhat persona level, even though I never spoke to him as I went through the factory gates a few minutes before 7 a.m. five days a week. My girlfriend Cindy, who also worked in the factory, thankfully in their offices where she didn't have to breathe in the hot-polluted air that frequently gave the workers endless headaches. On March 8, 1974, Cindy and I went to Madison Garden in New York City to see Wepner in his third bout of the trilogy he had with the talented Randy Neumann for the New Jersey Heavyweight title. Even though the match was in New York, the contest was held with New Jersey Rules, meaning two-minute rounds instead of the now universal three-minute rounds. The two boxers had split their first two mills, both by 12-round decisions. In their third and final fight, Wepner, despite being ten years older than Neumann at (35), won by stopping Neumann In the 6th round on a TKO in an exciting bout. Approximately two weeks later Cindy and I saw Wepner at a local Bayonne tavern named BAR 39 because it was on 39th street. Cindy and I approached Wepner who was sitting at the bar. Cindy was an incredibly beautiful girl. When she walked by, heads turned. She was blessed with a better figure than most Playmates of the month and was twice as beautiful as any of them that I saw in the plentiful Playboy magazines that were ubiquitous throughout the Western Electric factory. We simply wanted to extend our congratulations to our then-favorite boxer, The Bayonne Bleeder, Chuck Wepner.  I walked up to Wepner with a bottle of Budweiser in my hand and lightly tapped Chuck on his left arm, which felt like it had a brick implanted in it. I said, "Mr. Wepner, my girlfriend Cindy and I saw you knockout, Randy Neumann a couple of weeks ago at the Garden. We just wanted to congratulate you on your great championship victory."  Wepner was very polite and said, " Why thank you very much." He then stood up towering over my 5'9 being, and warmly shook my hand. Chuck then said "That's very nice of you. I appreciate it very much.  Say, can I buy you and your girlfriend a drink? I see you want a beer " Ias I gratefully nodded and responded, "Thank you, Sir." Chuck then said, "What can I get your girlfriend?  And then screamed at the top of his ample lungs "A glass of piss?" He then laughed and howled like he had made some kind of a clever joke.   Nobody was laughing but him. Walking away, I turned and said, "Thanks for doing something we will always remember you by." Wepner turned out to be an alcoholic cocaine addict, besides a huge asshole who went to prison. What goes around comes around. Chuck The Fuck was a big bully without a scintilla of class and a lousy ass boxer whose only asset was having a thick head to absorb all the punches he took. 'The Bayonne Bum'  who wasn't worth shit as a human being in my experience. Hopefully, he changed for the better. But I will always remember Wepner as 'Chuck The Fuck' a rotten punk and a lousy boxer who wouldn't have ever had the opportunity to be in the same ring as the great Muhammud Ali, except for being the beneficiary of having been born white. comments: De dakka marathi versions

I was eight(2006) when this came out in theaters. I will never forget the first day I seen this in theaters.

My Mom and My Dad were at their business after hours with my brother and I. They got into an argument and they didn‚Äôt talk to each other for a long time(that was fairly normal), but we agreed prior that we would go to the movies which we did often when I was a kid. My Mom wasn‚Äôt feeling like going, but my Dad thought it would do us good to go. So we did.

We four seen this movie together and we laughed throughout the entire movie, but whenever the movie was over, my Mom and my Dad walked out holding hands and my brother and I were attacked to the hip. We had a front row seat to seeing them be happy again. We went home as a family unit afterward.

My parents separated three years later, but I never forgot that pure moment in time: the movie was perfect and just what we all needed. A true comedy, but also a true family story. It made my family go back to being a true family that day.

No matter what became of the family in the future, we had that day and it was because of this film that the day ended up being the perfect day.

EDIT:

This movie remains one of my favorite movies of all time. I can‚Äôt recommend it enough. üòä‚ù§Ô∏è

Meh, when you think about it- AT LEAST it's not like Twilight with the sparkling and the "sexy vampire" stuff. Who knows, they might explain the historical accuracies as for the¬†people who made this¬†ARE professionals.

I liked how they captured the demonic side of Vampires, instead of trying to make them sexy, vampires in general are meant to be fowl, demonic creatures. Sure, maybe some sensuality was shown, but overall I thought they were accurate with the following things:

1. Dracula was a real guy, no arguing about that obviously

2. Dracula's superior power to other vampires, making him different from any other vampire

3. The dark, gritty, hellish side of vampires in general, instead of that sexy bullshit. pardon my language

4. I love how they portrayed his backstory, I mean a good man who would do anything to protect his family but eventually become an evil legend. Better than modern day vampiric sexuality

5. Sure, I get we got some critics out there who think this is some ridiculous trash covered with special effects, but who knows- it might do well.

6. I'm not judging your opinions, feel free to criticize, but we should at least give this film a chance, I for one already love it.
